---
alwaysApply: true
---

- Keep README.md focused on navigation and status only.
  A professor skimming it should understand what was built,
  who built it, and whether it works — in under 2 minutes.
- Do NOT include in README.md:
    - Code blocks longer than 5 lines
    - Full function signatures or docstrings
    - Mathematical derivations
    - Test output or coverage reports
    - Detailed troubleshooting steps
    - Long explanations of algorithms
- Route all detail into /docs:
    - docs/architecture.md   → system design, data flow diagram, module interaction
    - docs/data_pipeline.md  → cleaning steps, dataset facts, column decisions
    - docs/optimization.md   → objective function, KKT conditions, solver rationale
    - docs/backward_analysis.md → the 7 stages explained for a non-technical reader
    - docs/agent_design.md   → guardrails, agentic prompts, Gemini integration
    - docs/setup.md          → extended environment setup, secrets management
- If a change introduces content too long for README, move it to /docs
  and add a one-line link in README: "See docs/X.md for details."
